The paper deals with game theory and network analysis, which are both central topics in computer science. The use of a fixed, discrete set of strategies and a distance function to model player preferences suggests that the paper may fall under the category of algorithmic game theory (cs.GT). The focus on network coordination and the effects of neighbors' strategies suggests that the paper may also be relevant to social and information networks (cs.SI). The use of trees as a special case of the distance function suggests that the paper may also be relevant to data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The study of coordination games and the formation of opinions suggests that the paper may also be relevant to social computing (cs.SOC). Finally, the use of a distance function to model preferences suggests that the paper may also be relevant to information theory (cs.IT).
